\ul\b\i\fs24 5.Main Config file "f1_res.ini"\par
\par
\ulnone\b0\i0\fs20 This is where your current screen resolution and other settings are stored.\par
The "f1_res.ini" file is divided into six sections MAIN, HI_RES_PANEL, MOVIES, MAPS, IFACE and OTHER_SETTINGS.\par
\par
\par
\ul\b\i MAIN\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\par
\b Screen Dimensions (SCR_WIDTH = & SCR_HEIGHT =)\par
\b0 Set your custom resolution here.\b\par
\b0\par
\b Number of colours (COLOUR_BITS = 8)\b0\par
Can be set to 8 for 8bit colour (default) or 16 for 16bit colour.\par
\b\par
Text for Options Button (OPTIONS_TEXT = options)\par
\b0 Text to display beside the options button on the Main-menu.\b\par
\par
\par
\ul\i HI_RES_PANEL\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\par
\b Display List Descending/Ascending (DISPLAY_LIST_DESCENDING = 1)\b0\par
Here you can set the order of the resolution list in the Screen Settings Window. Descending order by default.\par
\par
\b Safer Display List (SAFER_DISPLAY_LIST=0)\b0\par
Set this to 1 if you experience crashing when using the Screen Settings Window.\par
\par
\par
\ul\b\i MOVIES\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\par
\b Movie Size (MOVIE_SIZE = 1)\b0\par
Here you can set how the movies stretch to the screen.\par
\par
\b Subtitle Area Height (SUBTITLE_AREA_HEIGHT = 66)\par
\b0 The Height of the area at the bottom of the screen for displaying subtitles\par
\par
\b Subtitle Position (SUBTITLE_POS = 10)\b0\par
The distance from the bottom of the screen to the bottom of the subtitles.\par
\par
\par
\ul\b\i MAPS\par
\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\b Ignore Map Edges (IGNORE_MAP_EDGES = 0)\par
\b0 Set to 0 (Off by default). If set to 1(On) this setting ignores the map edges preventing you scrolling outside the playable area of a map. \par
\par
\b Map Edges Folder Name (MAP_EDGES_NAME = F1_Original)\par
\b0 Sets the name of the folder containing ini config files for setting map edges. "F1_Original" is the default and contains variables for all maps used in Fallout.\b\par
\b0\par
\b Ignore Player Scroll Limits (IGNORE_PLAYER_SCROLL_LIMITS= 0)\par
\b0 Set to 0 (Off by default). If set to 1(On) this setting ignores the scroll limits from the player set below by the variables SCROLL_DIST_X and SCROLL_DIST_Y.\par
\cf3\par
\cf0\b Player Scroll Distance (SCROLL_DIST_X & SCROLL_DIST_Y)\b0\par
By default the scroll distance from the player is set to the\i  \ul screen edge + 1 tile\ulnone  \i0 in both directions. Setting a distance less than the screen edge can cause problems.\par
\par
\par
\ul\b\i IFACE\par
\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\b Height of the Viewable Map Area (IFACE_BAR_MODE = 0)\b0\par
By default the Viewable Map Area will sit above the Interface-Bar. Setting to 1 will lower the bottom of the Viewable Area to the bottom of the screen. Side bar graphics will be disabled in this mode.\par
\par
\b Iface Side-Bar Graphics Art (IFACE_BAR_SIDE_ART = 2)\par
\b0 Sets which optional art is used to fill the spaces either side of the Iface-bar.\par
Options are:\par
Set to 2 (default) for the Leather Pipboy Belt art created by me.\par
Set to 1 for the Corroded Metal art created by Simon Rawlins(Pixote).\b\par
\b0 Set to 0 for no side-bar art (Black).\b\par
\b0\par
\b Iface Side-Bar Graphics Orientation(IFACE_BAR_SIDE_ORI = 2)\b0\par
If set to 2 the Iface-bar side graphics extend from the Iface-Bar and are cut off where they meet the Screen edges.\par
If set to 1 the Iface-bar side graphics extend from the Screen edges and are cut off where they meet the Iface-Bar.\par
\par
\par
\par
\ul\b\i OTHER_SETTINGS\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\par
\b Error checking (MEM_CHECK_FLAG = 0)\par
\b0 Checks memory contents before writing. By default a message box will pop up (if there is a problem) giving you the name of a log file "f1_res_error.log" where the offsets of the errors will be stored. By default writing to memory will then be skipped and the program will resume. Further details on how errors are handled can be found in the "f1_res.ini".\par
\b\par
Notify Centre X (NOTIFY_CENTRE_X = 0)\par
\b0 Changes which way the notify panel scrolls horizontally. The Notify panel being where Sneak, Level up, Radiated etc are displayed. Choices are extend left, right or centre. Set to 0 by default (extends right from left).\par
\par
\b Dialog Screen Background (DIALOG_SCRN_BACKGROUND = 0)\par
\b0 When set to 1 this setting hides the Map and Iface-bar while viewing the Dialog Screen.\par
\par
\par
\ul\b\i\fs24 6. Map edges\par
\ulnone\b0\i0\fs20\par
The "f1_res\\Map_Edges" folder is where the scroll borders are set for each map in Fallout. The original scroll blockers were never designed to work at higher resolutions. So my solution in the end was to disable the original blockers and replace them with my own which I refer to here as map edges. Map edge data for all the regular maps are contained in the folder "f1_res\\Map_Edges\\F1_Original". The name of the map edges folder used can be changed in the "f1_res.ini" file. Other folders can also be created for other mods. The INI settings files within these folders can be created with the BIS Mapper using the Mapper2 Hi-Res Patch (Version 2.0+).\par
\par
\par
\b The map_edges INI file details\par
\b0 Each map edge folder contains INI config files referenced by name to the various maps in a mod.\par
Each INI file should contain at least one section labelled "default", which contains scroll boarder data for the used levels in a map. There may also be other sections for extra tweaks for particular resolutions. These other sections are named based on the resolution they are made for. For example a section made for a resolution of 1024 x 768 will be called "1024x768". If a complete match is not found settings will be grabbed from other sections with matching width's or height's falling back to the "default" section if custom settings are not found.\par
\par
This is an excerpt taken from the "ABBEY.ini" file made for the Abbey map of the Restoration Project 1.2.\par
\par
[default]\par
1N=7484\par
1S=28928\par
1E=28457\par
1W=19748\par
2N=12080\par
2S=19734\par
2E=20685\par
2W=14330\par
3N=10933\par
3S=20157\par
3E=17735\par
3W=15165\par
[1680x1050]\par
2N=9684\par
2S=21921\par
2E=20483\par
2W=13932\par
[1920x1080]\par
2N=9686\par
2W=13936\par
[1920x1200]\par
2N=9686\par
2W=13936\par
\par
The first part of each key name defines the map level. "1" for level one, "2" for level two and "3" for level three. The rest of the key name defines which edge your setting; "N" for north, "S" for south, "E" for east and "W" for west.\par
The key values themselves are hex tile numbers. They can refer to any hex tile running along the inside of the edge your setting up.\par
You only need to include keys for the map levels used.  For example if the Abbey map only used level 3, the whole section would look like this.\par
\par
[default]\par
3N=10933\par
3S=20157\par
3E=17735\par
3W=15165\par
\par
\b How it Works In Game\b0\par
When a map is loaded, the map edge variables are compared with the screen resolution. If the screen width is greater than the distance between the east and west edges and/or the screen height is greater than the north and south edges, then the distance between the two edges will be widened to compensate. It does this by adjusting the edge closest to the centre hexagonal tile as this edge has more room to move.\par
Also when a map loads it first centres in the middle of the edges. If this is out of bounds it will instead centre on the centre hexagonal tile 20100. This should not generally happen unless you\rquote re running the game at an extremely high resolution.\par
\par
Scrolling adjusts the position on the map of the hex tile located at the centre of the screen. Because the screen width and height won't necessarily be multiples of a hex tile width or height there will always be some variation on the location of a map edge between different resolutions. So when setting up a new map always test it at multiple resolutions.\par
